CHAPTER 2Regulations: information systems, advisory committee
	Information systems
		The Secretary of State may by regulations make provision about theestablishment and operation by the Health and Social Care Information Centre(“the Information Centre”) of one or more information systems for purposesrelating to—
			the safety and performance, including the clinical effectiveness, ofmedical devices that are placed on the market;
			the safety of individuals who receive or are treated with a medical device,or into whom a medical device is implanted;
			the improvement of medical device safety and performance through advancesin technology.
		The regulations may (among other things) make provision—
			specifying descriptions of information in relation to medical devices whichmay or must be entered or retained in an information system established undersubsection (1);
			requiring information to be provided to the Information Centre for thepurposes of its functions under the regulations;
			about the use or disclosure of information contained in an informationsystem established under subsection (1);
			requiring the Information Centre to have regard to specified matters inexercising its functions under the regulations.
		The provision mentioned in subsection (2)(b) may include provision—
			requiring specified persons or descriptions of persons to whom subsection(4) applies to provide information of a specified description to theInformation Centre;
			about the manner in which, and the time at which, those persons mustprovide that information;
			enabling the Information Centre to require specified persons ordescriptions of persons to whom subsection (4) applies to provide to it in amanner, and at a time, determined by the Information Centre—
			information of a specified description;
			information for specified purposes;
			any other information that the Information Centre considers it necessaryor expedient to have for the purposes of its functions under the regulations;
			about any procedural steps the Information Centre must follow in requiringa person to provide information to it;
			requiring specified persons or descriptions of persons to whom subsection(4) applies to record or retain information which they are, or may be,required to provide to the Information Centre under the regulations;
			in relation to the enforcement of any requirement imposed by or under theregulations.
		This subsection applies to any person who provides services, or exercisesany powers or duties, relating to medical devices.
		The descriptions of information specified in the provision mentioned insubsections (2)(a), (3)(a) and (3)(c)(i) may include—
			unique identifiers associated with medical devices;
			information in relation to individuals mentioned in subsection (1)(b);
			information about any procedure carried out in relation to a medical device(including information about any person involved in carrying out theprocedure).
		The provision mentioned in subsection (2)(c) may include provision about—
			the analysis by the Information Centre of information contained in aninformation system (whether alone or in combination with other information)for the purposes mentioned in subsection (1) or for other purposes;
			the publication by the Information Centre of information contained in aninformation system;
			the disclosure (other than by way of publication) of information containedin an information system to specified persons or descriptions of persons, orfor specified purposes;
			the use or further disclosure by any person of information disclosed tothem under the regulations.
		The provision mentioned in subsection (3)(f) may include provision applyingany provision of Chapter 3 of this Part (enforcement), with or withoutmodifications, in relation to a requirement imposed by or under theregulations.
		In this section, “specified” means specified in regulations undersubsection (1).
	Advisory committee
		The Secretary of State may by regulations establish, and make otherprovision about, a committee to advise the Secretary of State on such mattersrelating to medical devices as the regulations may specify.
		The regulations may (among other things) make provision about—
			the membership of the committee;
			the establishment by the committee of sub-committees;
			matters to which the committee may, or must, have regard;
			cooperation between the committee and the Commission on Human Medicines,and other bodies with expertise in relation to medical devices.
		The provision mentioned in subsection (2)(a) may include—
			provision about the number of members, their appointment, and thecircumstances in which a person ceases to be a member;
			requirements as to the independence of members from the Secretary of State;
			provision about the payment of remuneration and allowances to members.

CHAPTER 5Interpretation of Part 4
	Interpretation of Part 4
		In this Part, apart from in sections 32, 33 and 34 (provisions relating toforfeiture or seizure of medical devices), references to a medical deviceinclude references to a type of medical device.
		In this Part—
			  * the “appropriate appeals court” means— 
			in England and Wales, the Crown Court;
			in Scotland, the Sheriff Appeal Court;
			in Northern Ireland, a county court;
				  * the “appropriate lower court” means— 
			in England and Wales, a magistrates’ court;
			in Scotland, the sheriff;
			in Northern Ireland, a court of summary jurisdiction;
				  * “compliance notice” has the meaning given by section 21(2); 
				  * “data protection legislation” has the meaning given by section 3(9) of the Data Protection Act 2018; 
				  * the “enforcement authority” means— 
			in relation to medical devices which are ordinarily intended for private useor consumption—
			a local weights and measures authority in Great Britain or a district councilin Northern Ireland, or
			the Secretary of State, or
			in relation to other medical devices, the Secretary of State;
				  * “EU Medical Devices Regulations” means— 
			[Regulation (EU) 2017/745](/european/regulation/2017/0745?view=plain "Go toitem of legislation") of the European Parliament and of the Council of 5 April2017 on medical devices, amending [Directive2001/83/EC](/european/directive/2001/0083?view=plain "Go to item oflegislation"), Regulation [(EC) No178/2002](/european/regulation/2002/0178?view=plain "Go to item oflegislation") and Regulation [(EC) No1223/2009](/european/regulation/2009/1223?view=plain "Go to item oflegislation") and repealing Council [Directives90/385/EEC](/european/directive/1990/0385?view=plain "Go to item oflegislation") and [93/42/EEC](/european/directive/1993/0042?view=plain "Go toitem of legislation"), and
			[Regulation (EU) 2017/746](/european/regulation/2017/0748?view=plain "Go toitem of legislation") of the European Parliament and of the Council of 5 April2017 on in vitro diagnostic medical devices and repealing [Directive98/79/EC](/european/directive/1998/0079?view=plain "Go to item oflegislation") and [Commission Decision2010/227/EU](/european/decision/2010/0227?view=plain "Go to item oflegislation");
				  * “forfeiture order” has the meaning given by section 32(1); 
				  * “information notice” has the meaning given by section 24(2); 
				  * “manufacture” includes assembly; 
				  * “manufacturer” means any person who is a manufacturer for the purposes of any provision in the Medical Devices Regulations 2002 ([S.I. 2002/618](/id/uksi/2002/618?view=plain "Go to item of legislation")); 
				  * “medical device” includes— 
			medical devices to which the Medical Devices Regulations 2002 apply, and
			devices to which the EU Medical Devices Regulations apply;
				  * “medical devices provision” has the meaning given by section 17(2); 
				  * “relevant requirements” has the meaning given by section 16(1)(a); 
				  * “safety notice” has the meaning given by section 23(1); 
				  * “suspension notice” has the meaning given by section 22(2).

PART 6Report on operation of medicines and medical devices legislation
	Report on operation of medicines and medical devices legislation
		The Secretary of State must, before the end of the relevant period, publisha report on the operation of medicines and medical devices legislation.
		The report must, in particular, include an assessment of whether—
			some or all medicines and medical devices legislation should beconsolidated or otherwise restructured,
			provisions of medicines and medical devices legislation should be includedin regulations or Acts of Parliament, and
			powers to make regulations should be modified or repealed.
		In preparing the report, the Secretary of State must take into account anyreport relating to the operation of medicines and medical devices legislationmade by a Parliamentary Committee.
		The Secretary of State must lay a copy of the report before Parliament.
		In this section—
			  * “medicines and medical devices legislation” means— 
			the law relating to human medicines within the meaning of section 9(interpretation);
			the Veterinary Medicines Regulations 2013 ([S.I.2013/2033](/id/uksi/2013/2033?view=plain "Go to item of legislation"));
			the Medical Devices Regulations 2002 ([S.I.2002/618](/id/uksi/2002/618?view=plain "Go to item of legislation"));
			Parts 2 to 5 of this Act;
			regulations made under those Parts;
				  * “Parliamentary Committee” means a committee of the House of Commons or of the House of Lords or a joint committee of both Houses; 
				  * “relevant period” means the period of 5 years beginning with the day on which this Act is passed.
